Example: 
 import java.util.Scanner; 

 public class DoWhileLoopExample { 
 	public static void main(String[] args) { 
 		Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in); 
 		int number; 

 		do { 
 			System.out.print("Enter a positive number (0 to exit): "); 
 			number = scanner.nextInt(); 

 			if (number > 0) { 
 				System.out.println("You entered: " + number); 
 			} else { 
 				System.out.println("Invalid number!"); 
 		} 
 	} while (number != 0); 

 		System.out.println("Loop exited. Goodbye!"); 
 		scanner.close(); 
 	} 
 } 

 Output: 
 Enter a positive number (0 to exit): 5 
 You entered: 5 
 Enter a positive number (0 to exit): -2 
 Invalid number! 
 Enter a positive number (0 to exit): 10 
 You entered: 10 
 Enter a positive number (0 to exit): 0 
 Loop exited. Goodbye! 

 Example explained: 
 We use a do-while loop to repeatedly prompt the user to enter a positive number. The loop continues until the user enters 0 to exit the program.

Here's the basic syntax: 
 for (elementDataType element : collection) { 
 	// code to be executed in each iteration 
 }

Example: 
 int[] numbers = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}; 
 for (int number : numbers) { 
 	System.out.println(number); 
 } 

 Output: 
 1 
 2 
 3 
 4 
 5 

 Example explained: 
 We have an array called numbers containing integers. The foreach loop iterates over each element in the array, assigning it to the variable number. The loop body then executes, which in this case simply prints the value of number using System.out.println().

Primitive Data Types:
 int: Used to store whole numbers. 
 int myNumber = 42; 

 double: Used to store decimal numbers. 
 double myDecimalNumber = 3.14159; 

 boolean: Used to store true/false values. 
 boolean isTrue = true; 

 char: Used to store a single character.
 char myChar = 'A'; 

Reference Data Types:
 String: Used to store sequences of characters. 
 String myName = "John Doe"; 

 Array: Used to store a collection of elements of the same type. 
 int[] numbers = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}; 

 Object: Used to store instances of user-defined classes. 
 Date today = new Date(); 

 Class: Used to store the definition of a class. 
 Class<?> myClass = MyClass.class; 

 Interface: Used to store the definition of an interface. 
 interface MyInterface { 
 	void myMethod(); 
 }

String[] variable = {“Object”, “Values”, “List”, “Variables”, “Characters”}; 
 System.out.println(variable[0]); 
 Output: 
 Object

variable[0] = “subject”; 
 String[] variable = {“Object”, “Values”, “List”, “Variables”, “Characters”}; 
 variable[0] = “Subject”; 
 System.out.println(variable[0]); 
 Output: 
 Subject

 See the difference? The index 0 originally named “Object” was replaced with “Subject” upon changing the value.

// Single-dimensional array
int[] numbers = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };


    // Accessing a single-dimensional array element
int value = numbers[2];  // Retrieves the value 3


    // Multidimensional array (2D)
int[][] matrix = { { 1, 2, 3 }, { 4, 5, 6 } };


    // Accessing a multidimensional array element
int element = matrix[1][2];  // Retrieves the value 6


    In the above example, numbers is a single-dimensional array containing 5 elements, while matrix is a 2D array with 2 rows and 3 columns.
    Notice the difference in accessing elements: the single-dimensional array uses a single index (numbers[2]), while the 2D array requires two indices to specify the row and column (matrix[1][2]).


Multidimensional arrays provide a way to organize and represent data in multiple dimensions, enabling the handling of more complex structures and relationships among elements.

